desmos.instructions:
1. Type f(x) = (x+1)/(1-x)
2. Type h(x) = e^{-x}
3. Click the intersection point at (0, 1)

steps.content:
Factor $y$ out of the left side, then divide by the bracket to isolate $y$. This gives us the expression for the inverse function.

$$
\begin{aligned}
y(2x - 3) &= -1 - 5x \\
y &= \frac{-1-5x}{2x-3}
\end{aligned}
$$

So, the inverse function is:
$$f^{-1}(x) = \frac{-5x-1}{2x-3}$$

The domain of the inverse function consists of all real numbers except those that make the denominator zero. 

Set the denominator equal to zero to find the restriction:
$$
\begin{aligned}
2x - 3 &\neq 0 \\
2x &\neq 3 \\
x &\neq \frac{3}{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

**Domain:** $x \in \mathbb{R}, x \neq \frac{3}{2}$

Group all terms containing $y$ on one side and the other terms on the opposite side:

$$
\begin{aligned}
2xy - 3y &= -5x - 1 \\
y(2x - 3) &= -(5x + 1) \\
y &= \frac{-(5x+1)}{2x-3}
\end{aligned}
$$

This gives us the inverse function:
$$f^{-1}(x) = \frac{-5x-1}{2x-3}$$
